<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>John Wyclif</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Sep 18, 2001; substantive revision Tue May 6, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
John Wyclif (c. 1331&ndash;84) was one of the most important and
authoritative thinkers of the later Middle Ages. He was active in the
very crucial period of late Scholasticism, when new ideas and
doctrines began to accelerate the transition to modern ways of
thinking. On the one hand, he was a precursor of the Reformation by
leading a movement of opposition to the medieval Church and some of
its dogmas and institutions; on the other, he was the most prominent
English philosopher of the second half of the 14<sup>th</sup> century.
His logical and ontological theories represent the culmination of the
preceding realistic tradition of thought as well as the starting-point
of new forms of realism at the end of the Middle Ages. Many authors
active at the end of the 14<sup>th</sup> and beginning of the
15<sup>th</sup> centuries (e.g., Robert Alyngton, William Penbygull,
Johannes Sharpe, William Milverley, Roger Whelpdale, John Tarteys,
Paul of Venice), were deeply influenced by his metaphysics and
indebted to his approach to logic. But although his philosophical
system was rigorously designed, it contains puzzling conclusions and
suffers from a lack of clarity, both of which his followers attempted
to remedy. In this sense, Wyclif signposted the strategy Realists at
the end of the Middle Ages eventually adopted, rather than working out
its all its various implications himself.</p>
</div> 

